04320nam a22007095i 9781487596231DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20191978onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814875962317 a10.3138/97814875962312doi  a(DE-B1597)513701  a(OCoLC)1091661813  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 7aLAW0360002bisacsh04a345/.71/0752221 aGrosman, Brian A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Prosecutor :bAn Inquiry into the Exercise of Discretion /cBrian A. Grosman. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2019] 4c©1978  a1 online resource (138 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHeritage00tFrontmatter -- tPreface -- tPreface to the 1978 paperback edition -- tContents -- tI. Introduction -- tII. An Historical Perspective -- tIII. Initiating the Prosecution -- tIV. Discretion and Pre-trial Practices -- tV. The Administrative Perspective -- tVI. The Professional Perspective -- tVII. Reciprocal Relationships -- tVIII. Conflict and Compromise -- tIX. Reappraisal and Reform -- tAPPENDIX -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEvery day decisions made by prosecutors, before trial takes place, critically affect the rights of citizens; yet these decisions remain a grey area in the administration of criminal justice. In fact, there are considerable and important differences between what the prosecutor does and what the legal literature and judicial decisions say he should do. Very little is known about the powers wielded by prosecutors and the factors which influence their exercise of discretion. This inquiry focuses on the decision-making role of the prosecutor in pre-trial determinations. Professor Grosman describes and analyses the prosecutor's informal relations with the police and defence lawyers, and the significance these relationships have for the accused and for the fair administration of justice. Other areas examined include the decision to begin prosecution, the negotiated guilty plea, and the prosecutor's administrative bias. The study concludes with recommendations for judicial and legislative reform. Professor Grosman has added a preface to this edition outlining the changes that have occurred in recent years. A lucid and revealing description of the prosecutor's attitudes to criminal prosecution and its operation, this study contributes important insights valuable to lawyers and all those concerned with the administration of justice, and will be of interest to everyone concerned with social problems.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aProsecutionzCanadaxDecision making. 0aPublic prosecutorszCanada. 7aLAW / Ethics & Professional Responsibility.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999z978311049094740uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148759623140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487596231423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781487596231.jpg  a978-3-11-049094-7  University of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999c1933d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK